+# Rewrite Guard (Defensive Auto-Restore)
+
+`system_rewrite_guard.py` is a defensive script that automatically detects and rewrites unauthorized repository changes back to a trusted state.
+
+## What it protects
+
+- Unauthorized commits (author email allowlist + optional commit-signature checks).
+- Uncommitted changes (staged/unstaged edits).
+- Untracked files (optional wipe).
+- File-content drift via baseline SHA256 snapshots.
+
+## "For my systems alone" lock
+
+The script enforces both:
+
+- `owner_user`: Linux/macOS account username that is allowed to execute enforcement.
+- `host_lock`: hostname allowlist.
+
+If either does not match, enforcement aborts.
+
+## Quick start
+
+```bash
+python3 system_rewrite_guard.py init-policy
+python3 system_rewrite_guard.py snapshot-baseline
+python3 system_rewrite_guard.py enforce --rewrite
+```
+
+## Policy file
+
+The script stores policy in `.rewrite_guard_policy.json`.
+
+Important keys:
+
+- `allowed_author_emails`: only these commit author emails are trusted.
+- `require_verified_signature`: if true, each commit since `trusted_ref` must be signed and valid.
+- `trusted_ref`: reset target when rewrite occurs (example: `origin/main` or fixed commit SHA).
+- `protected_branches`: enforcement only runs on these branches.
+- `rewrite_uncommitted`: enables reset for dirty working tree.
+- `rewrite_untracked`: enables `git clean -fd`.
+
+## Forensic trail
+
+Before rewrite, the script creates a bundle in `.rewrite_guard/forensic_YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS/`:
+
+- reason
+- git status
+- recent log
+- working-tree diff (if present)
+- staged diff (if present)
+
+Event stream is appended to `.rewrite_guard/events.log`.
+
+## Continuous mode
+
+```bash
+python3 system_rewrite_guard.py daemon --interval 60 --rewrite
+```
+
+This checks every 60 seconds and rewrites when policy violations are found.
+
+## Important safety notes
+
+- Set `trusted_ref` to an immutable trusted target (signed tag or known commit SHA) for strongest safety.
+- If you set `trusted_ref` to `HEAD`, rewrite only removes local drift and does not remove already-accepted malicious commits.
+- Use branch protection and signed-commit enforcement on the remote as first-line defense.
