+# System Rewrite Guard
+
+`system_rewrite_guard.py` is a local defensive utility that can:
+
+- capture a trusted baseline of systems you own,
+- detect unauthorized drift (file-level and Git-level),
+- automatically restore from baseline snapshots,
+- maintain an audit trail for every detection and repair.
+
+## Why this exists
+
+If a malicious actor introduces changes through GitHub pushes, compromised credentials,
+or unsafe automation/tooling, this guard lets you force your own systems back to known-good state.
+
+## Quick start
+
+```bash
+python3 guard/system_rewrite_guard.py init-config
+# edit ~/.config/system_rewrite_guard/config.json
+python3 guard/system_rewrite_guard.py init-baseline
+python3 guard/system_rewrite_guard.py scan --repair
+```
+
+For continuous enforcement:
+
+```bash
+python3 guard/system_rewrite_guard.py daemon
+```
+
+## Configuration file
+
+Default location: `~/.config/system_rewrite_guard/config.json`
+
+Important fields:
+
+- `owner_emails`: only these commit author emails are accepted.
+- `require_signed_commits`: if true, unsigned/unverified `HEAD` is considered untrusted.
+- `allowed_remotes`: optional allow-list for acceptable `origin` remotes.
+- `systems`: list of directories to protect and restore.
+- `ignore_globs`: excludes files from baseline and drift checks.
+
+## Security model
+
+The guard classifies a system as untrusted if any of these occurs:
+
+1. Baseline drift (missing/extra/modified files).
+2. Git remote not on allow-list.
+3. Latest commit author email not owner-owned.
+4. Commit signature verification fails (if required).
+5. Working tree contains unexpected local edits.
+
+When `--repair` or `daemon` mode is used, untrusted systems are restored from baseline tarball snapshots.
+
+## Suggested deployment hardening
+
+- Run guard under a dedicated local user.
+- Store config and state on encrypted disk.
+- Restrict file permissions (`chmod 700` on state/config directories).
+- Keep baseline generation process offline and deliberate.
+- Pair with OS-level controls (immutable flags, SELinux/AppArmor, signed boot, MFA).
+
+## Important note
+
+This tool is designed for your systems only. Do not deploy it on systems you do not own or administer.
